My friend and I were looking for a place to eat close to his place in summer 2018, and we found this place on Yelp. We didn't realize it was a to-go place though, but we happily adopted it. When we entered, there were a lot of people around and actually quite noisy. My first impression wasn't too great though because it was dark and dingy, and not too clean-looking. The food was also pre-cooked, so it wasn't going to be fresh food. I also didn't really understand how to order food, but basically my friend and I ended up with some rice, meat, and vegetables. I don't remember exactly what I ate, but it was tasty but a bit lacking in flavor. The food being lukewarm also bothered me. There was a lot of food for the price of $12 post-tax. If we weren't too hungry, we could have shared one probably. Anyway, this was my first time eating Somalian food, and I'm excited to try more in the future!

I was so excited to order from here (on UberEats) after seeing all of the positive reviews. Sadly, the quality of food I received from Mogadishu was nothing of the sort. I ordered the spongy anjera with chicken legs which was advertised to come with spinach, cabbage, and split pea puree. What arrived was a thrown together dish of chicken legs and a tragic medley of random vegetables that were obviously warmed up from frozen, whole split peas, largely cut RAW onions, a few pieces of potato and a romaine salad. The chicken, though seasoned well, was dry. The best part of the meal was the anjera. So disappointed. I grew up with four siblings and this feels like one of those nights where my mom just didn't have it in her to cook and warmed up whatever was in the freezer. But even then she would do better than this. Tuh.

This place was awesome. I woke up wanting to try something new one morning, so I said African food. We walked into a restaurant filled with Somali men, eating and talking. It seemed like everyone knew everyone, almost like a band of brothers. People sat wherever they could. Very talkative. It was Ramadan, so these guys were hungry and happy to be having a meal. The guy behind the counter was super happy to help us. He seemed proud of his food. We got a togo platter, because there was nowhere to sit. He absolutely loaded a togo container with all sorts of different things. Here and there he'd confirm if we were interested in a particular item. Rice, beans, chicken, lettuce, salmon, a beef wrap, steamed veggies, a Somali version of a scotch egg, some flatbread, you name it. We went to the building next door and ate sitting on a planter box. Every single thing was delicious. Thank you for a great experience.
